## JsonDocument

This class holds the parsed model of the JSON payload.  It rents storage from an array pool, and this is `IDisposable` to return the resources back.

Like XmlDocument, this type only really has a creation routine (`Parse`) and access to the root element.

An instance takes a ReadOnlyMemory during construction, and holds that ReadOnlyMemory until Dispose (caller modification of the data between Parse and Dispose leads to non-deterministic, unsupported behavior).

## JsonElement

This type is effectively a cursor in the document.  It is tied to the document that created it, so when that document gets disposed the `ObjectDisposedException`s leak out from this types members.  To keep memory utilization at a minimum it is a struct which is effectively a union of what would otherwise be JsonArray, JsonObject, JsonComment, JsonString, JsonNumber, JsonProperty, and whatever we'd do for `true`/`false`/`null`. 

```C#
namespace System.Text.Json
{
    public sealed partial class JsonDocument : System.IDisposable
    {
        internal JsonDocument() { }
        public JsonElement RootElement { get { throw null; } }
        public void Dispose() { }
        public static JsonDocument Parse(ReadOnlyMemory<byte> utf8Json, JsonReaderOptions readerOptions) { throw null; }
    }
    public partial readonly struct JsonElement
    {
        // InvalidOperationException if Type is not StartObject
        // IndexOutOfRangeException when appropriate
        public JsonElement this[int index] { get { throw null; } }

        // InvalidOperationException if Type is not StartObject
        // KeyNotFoundException if the property is not found
        // Returns the element representing the value
        public JsonElement this[ReadOnlySpan<byte> utf8PropertyName] { get { throw null; } }
        public JsonElement this[ReadOnlySpan<char> propertyName] { get { throw null; } }
        public JsonElement this[string propertyName] { get { throw null; } }

        public JsonTokenType Type { get { throw null; } }

        // StartArray: Enumerates the values
        // StartObject: Enumerates PropertyName0, Value0, PropertyName1, Value1, ...
        // default: throw InvalidOperationException
        public JsonElement.ChildEnumerator EnumerateChildren() { throw null; }

        // InvalidOperationException if Type is not correct.
        public int GetArrayLength() { throw null; }
        public string GetString() { throw null; }
        public bool GetBoolean() { throw null; }

        // InvalidOperationException if Type is not correct
        // FormatException if the value does not parse (e.g. "1e1" as Int32, or a BigInteger value)
        public double GetDouble() { throw null; }
        public int GetInt32() { throw null; }
        public long GetInt64() { throw null; }
        public ulong GetUInt64() { throw null; }

        // The escaped string for PropertyName and String
        // bool.TrueString and bool.FalseString for boolean types
        // Otherwise the UTF-8 raw data transcoded to UTF-16
        public override string ToString() { throw null; }

        // Try- variants of the non-integer indexers (no KeyNotFoundException)
        public bool TryGetProperty(ReadOnlySpan<byte> utf8PropertyName, out JsonElement value) { throw null; }
        public bool TryGetProperty(ReadOnlySpan<char> propertyName, out JsonElement value) { throw null; }
        public bool TryGetProperty(string propertyName, out JsonElement value) { throw null; }

        // These two methods are the only place that the UTF-8 encoding leak through.
        // If we lock the type in to UTF-8 processing then these get softened.
        public bool TryGetRawValue(out ReadOnlyMemory<byte> rawValue) { throw null; }
        public bool TryCopyRawValue(Span<byte> destination, out int bytesWritten) { throw null; }

        // InvalidOperationException on the wrong Type (matches Utf8JsonReader)
        // false on precision problems
        public bool TryGetValue(out double value) { throw null; }
        public bool TryGetValue(out int value) { throw null; }
        public bool TryGetValue(out long value) { throw null; }
        public bool TryGetValue(out ulong value) { throw null; }

        public partial struct ChildEnumerator
        {
            private object _dummy;
            public JsonElement Current { get { throw null; } }
            public ChildEnumerator GetEnumerator() { throw null; }
            public bool MoveNext() { throw null; }
        }
    }
}
```

In order to keep the overhead low this type does not support data manipulation (insert/append, delete, or update) or ReadOnlySequence (`SequencePosition` is itself the size of the current per-token state, and is not blittable).

